  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2812200010" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2812200010" />
    <a title="Henk" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/76202320-henk"><img alt="Henk" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1557871304p2/76202320.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2812200010?book_show_action=true">Aug 25, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Henk" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Henk" href="/user/show/76202320-henk">Henk</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9781787331501" href="/book/show/41955384-on-earth-we-re-briefly-gorgeous">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/76202320-henk?shelf=owned">owned</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2812200010" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4101756839043389039"><b>Beautiful and poetic, a meditation on growing up in rural, dying America as a gay immigrant</b><br/><i>That time at the Chinese butcher, you pointed to the roasted pig hanging from its hook. “The ribs are just like q person’s after they’re burned.” You let out a clipped chuckle, then paused, rook out your pocketbook, your face pinched, and recounted our money.</i><br/><br/><b>Mother and Son</b><br/><i>When does a war end? When can I say your name and have it mean only your name and not what you left behind?</i><br/><a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/41880609.On_Earth_We_re_Briefly_Gorgeous' title='On Earth We&apos;re Briefly Gorgeous by Ocean Vuong' rel='nofollow noopener'>On Earth We&apos;re Briefly Gorgeo</a></span>
  <span id="freeText4101756839043389039" style="display:none"><b>Beautiful and poetic, a meditation on growing up in rural, dying America as a gay immigrant</b><br /><i>That time at the Chinese butcher, you pointed to the roasted pig hanging from its hook. “The ribs are just like q person’s after they’re burned.” You let out a clipped chuckle, then paused, rook out your pocketbook, your face pinched, and recounted our money.</i><br /><br /><b>Mother and Son</b><br /><i>When does a war end? When can I say your name and have it mean only your name and not what you left behind?</i><br /><a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/41880609.On_Earth_We_re_Briefly_Gorgeous" title="On Earth We're Briefly Gorgeous by Ocean Vuong" rel="nofollow noopener">On Earth We're Briefly Gorgeous</a> starts of with a lot of supressed violence from Little Dog’s mom, channeled towards him while growing up in Hartford, Connecticut. <br />Little Dog as narrator tells the poignant story of him growing up as the son of an immigrant Vietnamese, by writing a letter to his illiterate mother. His name is poetically explained: (<i>To love something, then, is to name it after something so worthless it might be left untouched - and alive</i>) and the poetic title of the book is only further augmented by the language, that is lush and full of beautiful images and metaphors. This while the underlying story is quite brutal, encompassing not just the perils and sacrifices of his mother, but also the dangers of growing up in rural America in the midst of an opioid epidemic.<br /><br />Little Dog acting as his mother and grandmother’s interpreter, culminating in a scene where he explains as an eight year old that he was her child, born from her asshole to a store assistent at Sears, since there is a taboo to talk about the genitalia in Vietnamese, is both saddening as sometimes hilarious.<br /><br />An other scene I admired was the depiction of how the lack of language frustrates his mom, when Little Dog tells about being bullied, and she hits him, before coming up with the solution he needs to become bigger and she starts to feed him gallons of milk each and every morning. <br /><br />There is so much deep emotions tied to these sections of the book, to the life stories of his mother and grandmother, and so many beautiful sentences on how Little Dog navigates the world and reflects on historical violence:<br /><br /><i>I touch the world not as myself but as an echo of who I was.<br /><br />Memory is a choice. You said that once, with your back to me, the way a god would say it.<br /><br />Because a bullet without a body is a song without ears.<br /><br />She examined her hand, as if to make sure it still existed, then dropped it.<br /><br />“Remember”, you said each morning before we stepped out in cold Connecticut air, “don’t draw attention to yourself. You’re already Vietnamese.”</i><br /><br /><b>Son and lover</b><br /><i>I studied him like a new word.</i><br /><br />In a certain way I feel the book could have revolved solely around the family relations without any problem, but <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/4456871.Ocean_Vuong" title="Ocean Vuong" rel="nofollow noopener">Ocean Vuong</a> also weaves in a touching love story. His relationship with Trevor, a hillbilly, redneck, drugs doing first boyfriend, feels like a train crash you see happening in slow motion. Actually the coming out to his mother doesn't seem to go very disasterous, but show the unbridgeable gap between his mothers language and his own world when there is no fitting, non-colonial word that doesn’t refer to pedophilia to describe homosexuality in Vietnamese.<br /><br />His reflections on his first relationship, and the power dynamics in this (with Trevor asserting that this is only a phase for him, but something forever for Little Dog, also tied to who penetrates who) are very well done in my opinion. We are offered phrases as: <i>Sometimes being offered tenderness feels like the very proof that you’ve been ruined.</i><br />And genuine tenderness comes back for instances in the depiction of the first time the boys have sex with each other.<br /><br />In the end the power of class in modern day America, with overdoses and immigrants barely scraping a living together, opioid epidemics and derelict towns with trailer parks, take precedent. <br />But the elegy to a first love is beautiful, nonetheless: <i>We were exchanging truths, I realized, which is to say, we were cutting one another. &amp; You wore a face.</i><br /><br />Intimacy (mostly physical and sometimes tender with his first lover while having sex) and a lack of possibility of being truly intimate with the one’s closest to you (like how he longs for being a word and his whole being, laid down besides his mother, just to convene everything he is) is also beautifully tackled by Ocean Vuong.<br /><br />I was immersed into On Earth We're Briefly Gorgeous, and found it both convincing and emotionally impactful. The language is sometimes too flowery one could say, but Vuong offers us gems of sentences and I feel he is a very great literary talent who captures both the power of stories and loss:<br /><i>...where to be lost is never to be wrong, but simply more.</i></span>
  <a data-text-id="4101756839043389039" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


